	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Wood Elf Druid levels 0-30+</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:sethompson@adelphia.net">S. E. Thompson</a> | 
		            12/7/2001 2:38:59 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Faz's Druid leveling guide <BR>
<BR>
This is a bit narrative and a bit self-help guide, with pointers on the way I WOULD have done things had I known then what I know now. Some of my recollections regarding lower level play may be a little fuzzy, but should be helpful. My mid-level experiences are fresh in my mind and probably more helpful.<BR>
<BR>
As a General strategy, remember you will receive new spells every 5 levels. These spells are most potent as soon as you get them because they only get slightly more effective as you level up but you must fight higher level enemies with them. So, you will see more impressive results with your new level 19 spells at level 19 than when you are level 23 fighting tougher monsters with the same spell. In general, I&#8217;ve broken these sections up into level splits where I think I would have made the transition between hunting tactics and zones. They basically follow the spell progression, although they should be considered valid +/- 2 levels.<BR>
<BR>
Starting Out <BR>
<BR>
As a Wood Elf, you will obviously start in the tree city of Kelethin, located in Greater Faydark. Your first challenge is finding your guild in Kelethin. www.eqatlas.com can help, but even that is confusing because there are multiple levels of platforms and the maps can be hard to decipher. In fact, at level 30, I'm only now comfortable running from place to place on the platforms. As well, plan on falling off at least once and dying - it happens to all of us. <BR>
<BR>
The easiest rule of thumb is to run around on the ground and then up one of the three selected lifts. Kelethin is shaped like a giant letter &quot;L&quot;, the northern-most part is where you'll find the higher level mobs and the &quot;orc&quot; lift. The &quot;newbie&quot; lift is the farthest South and East at the foot of the &quot;L&quot;. The &quot;POD&quot; lift is at the inside corner of the basic &quot;L&quot; shape. To find your way around, the following tricks can be used:<BR>
<BR>
From the newbie lift to the POD lift, walk off the lift ramp and turn left 90 degrees. Walk straight to the POD lift. Reverse this to get from the POD lift to the Newbie lift. These two lifts are very close together and can just about be seen from each other. To get from the POD lift to the ORC lift, walk off the POD lift ramp and turn left 90 degrees. Walk straight to the ORC lift. This is a much longer walk underneath the platforms. To get from the ORC lift to the POD lift walk up the ORC lift ramp and keep walking in a straight line (off the lift and keep going on the grass).<BR>
<BR>
Once you learn this, you can run from lift to lift to lift quite easily. The most important lift for you is the POD lift. Go up the POD lift and straight across the platform to the bridge opposite the lift. This takes you to another platform. At this platform you will see a large ramp leading up to the left. This platform up the left ramp houses the Bank of Kelethin. So use the lift-to-lift method and always go up the POD lift, straight across and up to the left. This technique will get you in and out of the bank easily. You'll quickly see that the Bank of Kelethin is the center of activity for most of Norrath and the platform is generally overcrowded. So much so that I actually experience delays when first moving onto that platform as all the player info is loaded.<BR>
<BR>
Now that you can find the bank easily, you're on your way to the Druid guild. Across from the ramp to this platform is another ramp leading up. Take this ramp up then take the next one down to the Ranger Guild. On this platform, across from the entrance ramp, again, is another ramp leading down. Take this to the Druid Guild. So, simply speaking: Up the POD lift, across to the next platform, up to the left ramp (BANK), across, up and down the ramp (RANGER GUILD), across and down the ramp (DRUID GUILD).<BR>
<BR>
Another note for newbies in Greater Fay. It is a relatively simple zone, but don't trust yourself to follow the trails - they fork and twist. I can't count how many times, in the heat of battle on Orc Hill, I ran for my life to the nearest trail and followed it, hoping to get to a lift and the safety of a waiting guard, only to end up in the middle of another Orc encampment and swift death.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 1-2 (Bats)<BR>
<BR>
To begin your adventure, stay around the newbie and POD lifts killing bats, and only bats, until about level 3. Resist all temptation to run and sell your looted bat wings. Instead save them until you have a stack of 20. Then use an auction to sell the stack for 4-5 PP instead of the measly few gold you would have gotten from a merchant. Batwings are used by spellcasters (including druids) to cast a levitate spell. By the time you need these batwings for your own use, however, you will have plenty enough money to buy a stack for 4-5 PP. The reason for only killing bats is that you can make much more money selling batwings in the same number of kills, so use your health and mana getting the most cash for your efforts. Occasionally the new tailor will offer to buy ruined wolf pelts and the infrequent Necro will send an auction message looking to buy bone chips from skeletons, however, this is not as common.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 3-4 (Spiders and Orc Pawns)<BR>
<BR>
At about level 3 or 4 start spending more time around the POD lift than the newbie lift and start hunting widow hatchlings and orc pawns. Loot from the Orc Pawns can either be used by you (such as basic cloth articles) or sold to merchants. There is no real player demand for Orc loot, except a few unimpressive quests, so simply sell the loot. Take the loot from the Orc Pawns, sell it to merchants and buy backpacks &#8211; you&#8217;ll need the storage space very soon. The spiderlings will drop spiderling silk &#8211; this is even more valuable than the batwings, so save it. It is used for beginning tailoring and stacks of 20 can be auctioned for 5-10pp. If you intend to take up tailoring as a tradeskill, save them instead of selling them. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
While hunting in this area, keep an eye out for the occasional Orc Centurion &#8211; don&#8217;t accidentally attack one thinking it is an Orc Pawn. If you see a couple that /con blue to you then hunt them down also. Be careful, however, when hunting Orcs because they tend to agro easily and gang up very, very quickly. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Levels 5-8 (Orc Hill and CB Belts)<BR>
<BR>
Level 5 brings your first new spells <BR>
<BR>
This is where growing up in Kelethin gets exciting! Find your way to the Orc Lift and head straight North of the ramp. You&#8217;ll see a trail begin, which you will lead you to chaos, fun and experience. To get familiar with this area stop before the trail ends and wait for the occasional single Orc Centurion. Make sure to /con them first and avoid any reds or yellows. Again, watch for the &#8220;adds&#8221; and &#8220;trains&#8221; which are a minute-by-minute part of this area. In fact, its fun to stand by and watch a train of 5 Orcs tearing down the trail, after some poor soul who built there first train. This will happen to you. Fact. Plan on it. The key to survival is being prepared and reacting appropriately. The first step is not going beyond the end of the trail and NOT getting disoriented. When you have an additional MOB on you , you must get back to the Orc lift fast, so the guards can dispatch these enemies for you. An important point to recognize is the wide agro radius that Orcs have &#8211; seemingly larger than any other MOB. The positive side of this experience is that you&#8217;ll learn the finer points of avoiding wandering MOBS and have a whole new appreciation for aggro&#8217;s as you move higher in levels. <BR>
<BR>
The Orc Lift ramp is like &#8220;healing and medding central&#8221;, with players sitting all around the ramp recovering under the protection of the nearby guards. Now the danger here is that sometimes the guards are slow to react and you may have to run around the lift a few times before the guards wake up and help you. <BR>
<BR>
For &#8220;Add Control&#8221; as I call it, you want to watch your fight from an overhead or 3rd angle camera view, so hit the F9 key four times. Practice zooming the camera view around with your mouse and watching your character for an approaching MOB during a fight. Otherwise you&#8217;ll be fighting an enemy in front of you, without realizing there is an identical enemy hitting you from behind &#8211; the messages look like one MOB is hitting you and only after you die and see two or more enemies standing over your corpse do you realize what happened. Learning this alternate view skill becomes crucial while fighting around this area and is a skill you will come to depend upon throughout your life in Norrath. The difficulty with using this view in a forested or indoor area is that the camera can not exceed the physical boundaries of the area (walls, etc) and can become obstructed by objects (trees, etc.) so you&#8217;ll need the practice moving the camera angle around during a fight.<BR>
<BR>
At the end of this trail you will get comfortable fighting Orc Centurions and escaping trains. At this point, you will begin your first quest and join in your first groups. In a group, and only in a group, head straight past the end of this Orc trail. After it ends you&#8217;ll see a few huts on your right and just past these you will see the infamous &#8220;Orc Hill&#8221;. Park your group on top of this hill and let the carnage begin. There is often enough Orc traffic nearby for three separate groups to be camped here fighting simultaneously. The danger in that is the close proximity of all those Orcs. If a group gets killed, there are several angry Orcs standing around looking for a new target &#8211; instant &#8220;adds&#8221; to your fight. Most important to surviving Orc Hill is finding your way back to the lift. Get familiar with it and don&#8217;t trust the trails &#8211; there is one deceptively similar looking trail that leads you into more Orcs if you follow it. The easiest rule of thumb is to look down from Orc Hill at the multiple huts. You will see two right next to each other. Draw an imaginary line past the door of each hut &#8211; this imaginary line points straight to the lift (forget about the trail, learn this direction).<BR>
<BR>
During this period of growth you will get your first really valuable loot off of Orc Centurions. These are crushbone belts &#8211; save them all! There is a dwarf in the back corner of South Kaladim that collects these as a quest item. In reality, you&#8217;re supposed to talk to him, receive his instructions and bring him the belts, four at a time. You don&#8217;t have to as he doesn&#8217;t &#8220;remember&#8221; who he talked to &#8211; just ask around to find him and give him the belts four at a time. He will reward you with a little cash, some tattered leather armor, experience and faction improvements. If you collect enough belts (say 32 or so) , you can gain nearly an entire level just from this quest. Collecting the belts is fairly easy as they are a common drop off Orc Centurions (I&#8217;d say one out of every four) and there are always extra corpses lying around that you can loot. Other players who either don&#8217;t want the loot, died or ran before looting leave behind these extra corpses. On a busy day, I&#8217;ve filled a backpack with belts without even killing a single Orc. <BR>
<BR>
On Orc Hill, you&#8217;ll get your first exposure to a new danger &#8211; the spellcasting MOB. This one takes the form of an Orc Oracle who can inflict some heavy damage as well as some nasty spell effects. This is the first time you&#8217;ll fight an enemy that remains at a distance and your group will quickly learn that you need work together to finish this one off first before fighting the others that are hitting you. That&#8217;s an important group tactic you will learn called &#8220;assisting&#8221;. Especially at higher levels where there are strategic reasons to selectively pick off one MOB in a group, it is important that you are attacking the correct one. To do this best, identify one member of your group as the primary &#8220;tank&#8221; who will hit the front lines, take the worst beating and batter away. Everyone else in the group should target this group member and issue the /assist command. This will ensure that they are all hitting the same MOB and the correct one. Chances are, your group at this level may be low and not understand this concept, so you will need to explain it to them. If they can&#8217;t get it right its not crucial, but it&#8217;s a technique that will become absolutely essential in about 10 levels.<BR>
<BR>
Once you have a healthy collection of CB Belts, and are probably around level 7 or 8, take your first trip into another zone. The destination we are looking for is the City of Kaladim in the Butcherblock Mountain zone just East of Great Faydark. Refer to www.eqatlas.com to find your way around. It&#8217;s fairly easy to find Kaladim, but finding the correct NPC can be tricky. He&#8217;s named Canloe Nusback and can be found in the building behind the pool in SOUTH Kaladim. Find the room with the large kitchen table, go through the other door and take the hall to the right. Canloe is in the room at the end of this hall.<BR>
<BR>
This combination of Orc Hill fighting and CB belt quests should bring you to level 9 fairly quickly, at which time you&#8217;ll need to move on to another hunting territory. Many people try their luck in Crushbone, just North of Orc Hill but I don&#8217;t recommend this zone. It&#8217;s fairly cramped, the Orcs are higher level and the tend to gang up on players very quickly. Crushbone seems to be just a place to create trains and run to the nearby zone, leaving a collection of angry MOB&#8217;s standing around.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 9-13 (NoRo)<BR>
<BR>
Without the services of a friendly porting Wizard or higher Druid, you&#8217;ll need to take the boat from ButcherBlock Mountains to the city of Freeport on the continent of Antonica. Before leaving the city, beg or buy a bind from someone at the East Gate of East Freeport. Don&#8217;t try venturing out until you get this bind. Otherwise you&#8217;ll have a long run back to the BB docks and a 20 minute boat ride (in your underwear) back to your corpse.<BR>
<BR>
Head straight out of the East gate and zone into the Northern Desert of Ro. Here you can solo anything that cons blue to you. If you haven&#8217;t yet obtained your cure poison and cure disease spells then avoid the mummies (disease) and the snakes and spiders (poison). Scarabs are higher level than spiders but don&#8217;t pack the added punch of poison so you may be better off attacking them without a cure poison spell. If you have cure poison, kill all the spiders and collect spider silk (its different than spiderLING silk but still used for tailoring) which sells for 20pp per stack.<BR>
<BR>
The real experience here will be in groups at the three Derv camps. Avoid &#8220;Derv 1&#8221; as there is a very nasty NPC there named Dorn. My favorite camp was &#8220;Derv 3&#8221; as found on www.eqatlas.com maps. The interesting thing about Derv 3 is its location to the nearest zone. If you get in trouble, you may think to run away from the camp, but don&#8217;t! Instead run right past the camp to the closer southern zone, which leads into the Oasis of Marr.<BR>
<BR>
In the Derv camps, you can collect bronze weapons, which sell for 2-3 PP each and your first magical items the Cutthroat Insignia Ring that boasts a +2 Dexterity enhancement. Wear these rings as you find them and then auction them off later for 4-5 PP each. Camping these Derv&#8217;s should get you to level 15. <BR>
<BR>
At this point, you will begin to have more of a supportive role for your group instead of an offensive role. You&#8217;ve now got three important tools in your collection: Lesser Healing, Harmonize and SOW. Your job will be to harmonize the camp so your puller can grab one MOB at a time and keep the fights manageable. Your other job is to be back-up healer, in case your cleric runs out of mana and then you must keep your group SOW-ed at all times so they can always escape. If you&#8217;re low on mana make sure everyone has SOW before using it up. SOW-ing your party is your number one concern and must never be compromised.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 14-18 (Oasis)<BR>
<BR>
Somewhere around level 16 you&#8217;ll want to head into Oasis, just South of Northern Ro. This will be your first highly populated hunting zone and a chance to begin selling your services. The meeting place for this zone is the dock, where everyone tends to congregate to heal and med. At this location you can shout that you are &#8220;sowing for donations&#8221;. Plenty of players will take you up on this offer. Several will beg you for a free SOW. The decision is yours to make. Making alliances is important and that pitiful player you help now may become that level 50 cleric who rezzes you later in life. However, there is so much demand for SOW and so many people in this location that you could, quite literally, spend 100% of your time medding on the docks, sowing away all your mana and medding again (repeat ad nauseum). Some players just don&#8217;t understand that this means you can&#8217;t fight and get loot or experience so you need to let them know. In this zone, the going donation for a SOW seems to be 1-2PP. You&#8217;ll also be called upon to cure the occasional rabies, disease or poison at the docks. These I always do graciously.<BR>
<BR>
In Oasis you can group at the Orc camps or an area of high traffic nicknamed Orc Highway. It is relatively safe except for the high level Specters and Sand Giants who you stand no chance of surviving. There is also one particular type of Orc there called &#8220;A Orc Warrior&#8221; instead of &#8220;An Orc Warrior&#8221;. This one is higher level and should be avoided. A named crocodile called Lockjaw is a very high level quest-related MOB who should be avoided.<BR>
<BR>
Most importantly, for you, Oasis is where you first really hone your unique Druid fighting expertise called &#8220;kiting&#8221;. Kiting is the process of fighting a monster from a distance, keeping it following you while you blasting it before it can get close enough to hit you. It appears as if you are pulling the enemy behind you, like on a kite string. There are plenty of references on Kiting, so this will just summarize the basics:<BR>
<BR>
To Kite, you first make sure you have SOW on yourself. In fact, there is never time you should be without SOW.<BR>
<BR>
Find a MOB and /con it. Once selected, target the MOB and cast snare on it. If the MOB is ensared, back up a little bit and cast a DOT spell on it, such as stinging swarm, then turn and run. You do NOT have to be facing the MOB to cast a spell on it so you can kite in a couple different ways. Because of the danger of aggroes, you should never run backward while kiting.<BR>
<BR>
I prefer switching to 3rd angle camera view and watching the fight from a distance. This way I know if I&#8217;m running toward another MOB that will aggro on me. <BR>
<BR>
Another way is to simply run away, while looking ahead. Stop and cast a DD spell. If your target is out of range, just keep trying until it gets hit. Then run again. The only drawback of this method is that you cannot see when the MOB gives up the fight, although you&#8217;ll soon learn when they&#8217;ll turn based on their health bar.<BR>
<BR>
Depending upon other factors, you may choose to finish the MOB off with DD spells or attack directly. At lower levels your melee attack is still reasonably comparable to your DD spells so it&#8217;s probably more prudent to save mana and attack a MOB once it turns. If the snare holds it will stop attacking and NOT run away.<BR>
<BR>
For practice, Caimens and Croc&#8217;s are great kiting quarry and as you grow in expertise you&#8217;ll become versed in fear-kiting and eventually quad-kiting. <BR>
<BR>
I&#8217;ve also read a lot about charming animals, and tried it numerous times. Perhaps you can have better luck, but I found it useless because the charm breaks so quickly and I found myself with TWO angry MOB&#8217;s on me. And even if it ever did work, you only get 50% of the experience, unless you kill your pet first.<BR>
<BR>
Oasis should carry you to level 19 quite easily at which time you&#8217;ll be ready to move on.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 19&#8211;28 (LOIO)<BR>
<BR>
Lake of Ill Omen seems to be the most popular hunting ground in all of Norrath, with the hub of activity located in the &#8220;Mill&#8221;. Again, refer to a map to find your way around here. Druid Kiting can be done carefully in Illomen but you may want to cast levitate if you&#8217;re staying around the mountains. I preferred kiting near the mouth of the stream to Firiona Vie or along the shoreline in a placed called &#8220;The Alley&#8221;. <BR>
<BR>
At level 30, I can find a wide variety of blue MOBS here, mostly near the Sarnak fort. Grouping at the Sarnak for is terrific fun with plenty of pull action and some high strategy fighting. This is where enchanters really begin to shine, by debuffing, de-resisting and mesmerizing MOB&#8217;s so you&#8217;ll need to be using the /assist tactic from earlier on.<BR>
<BR>
There are basically five classes of enemies in LOIO: Iksars, Goblins, Sarnaks, Sabertooth Tigers and Skeletons. The Tigers and Skeletons never give up the fight no matter how wounded they are. The other three will always turn away if they are nearing death so you have a chance to do more damage to these three without getting hit at the end of a fight. I&#8217;d rather fight a Sarnak with two bubbles of health left than a Skeleton with one bubble left.<BR>
<BR>
While in LOIO collect as many excellent sabertooth hides as you can &#8211; these auction for 15PP each but are heavy so you don&#8217;t want to carry them around.<BR>
<BR>
The Sarnaks tend to be well armored and harder to hit, but slower than the other MOB&#8217;s in LOIO. The Iksar&#8217;s and Tigers are the fastest and if they resist a snare or your SOW expires, you are in trouble.<BR>
<BR>
The Goblins seem to be the easiest hunting of all of these enemies and the Goblin Battlemaster drops a quest-related Goblin Bracer which can be turned in (in groups of four) to the ranger guild in FV for experience and +CHA ringmail rewards.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 29-3? (Air service now open! and SK)<BR>
<BR>
Lake of Ill Omen can easily provide tons of experience through the early-mid thirties, but after ten levels here, I needed a change. A guild friend brought me to The Plains of South Karana, which quickly became my favorite hunting spot. I wish I had left LOIO, and come here, sooner. <BR>
<BR>
By this point you will have become familiar with porting yourself all over Norrath. Since there are Druid rings pretty well spaced, I bound myself in LOIO and simply ported around to my new hunting grounds (or corpse as the case may be). When hitting level 14, SOW made you everyone&#8217;s favorite friend (or begging target). At level 29, your new &#8220;Circle&#8221; spells make you even more important in others lives. These spells allow you to port your entire group to a variety of locations (Butcher Block Mountains, West Commons, Toxxulia Forest, Surefall Glade and North Karana). This is where you can really start to make some money. Without being stingy and just offering &#8220;porting for donations&#8221; most people will gladly pay you 10PP to avoid a boat ride and long run. Often, you&#8217;ll be able to port several people at once and some people will pay even more if they are desperate. I&#8217;ve made about 300PP in five days of casual play, just porting other people around (10-15PP per person X 5 ports = 50-75 easy Plat in a night).<BR>
<BR>
About this time, I moved from grouping back to solo-ing again and SK is the best place I&#8217;ve ever seen for a druid to hunt in. It&#8217;s long and flat with tons of space to run and kite. It&#8217;s also inhabited mostly by wild animals which basically never aggro on a druid so you can even sit down in the middle of nowhere to med up safely. <BR>
<BR>
An interesting example of this incredible arrangement is the centaur village (a series of three stables in the Northeast corner of this zone). A druid can literally sit down inside the stables, between the centaurs to med, stand up, kill the centaurs, and sit back down again without fear of getting aggroed. The centaurs have no faction and only the ones involved in your fight remember to attack you. In fact, you can kill all the centaurs you want, loot them and sell the loot to the centaur merchant in the next hut over who, by the way, is glad to deal with you.<BR>
<BR>
The centaurs con blue to my level 30 druid (with the occasional yellow) but they are rated low. They hit hard and run very fast so you should be cautious when fighting them.<BR>
<BR>
My favorite hunting place (now anyway) is the entrance to Splitpaw lair (called &#8220;Infected Paw&#8221; now). This is located directly south of the bridge from NK and a little over halfway through the zone at &#8211;3000. It consists of a small mound of hills with three spires around it. In the center of the mound is a cave that leads underground into the lair itself. This location is ideal because it is a very convenient zone boundary in case you get in trouble. This is the place to run to and its very close. The lair is home to a clan of nasty gnolls who have taken over the caverns and guard it from above. These guards up above in South Karana are the targets of our hunting. The spawn at each of the three spires and then on the side of the hill, so there are basically four spots where groups will camp. The gnolls that pop here generally stay in position until attacked but there are the occasionally &#8220;runners&#8221; that pop and run around the perimeter of the area. <BR>
I&#8217;ve seen these camps backed up with groups waiting their turn and I&#8217;ve also been there when all four camps were open and I couldn&#8217;t med fast enough to keep up with all the spawns. In that case, I selectively pull the ones with weapons because I know I can sell them for several plat.<BR>
<BR>
These MOB&#8217;s are ideal for a druid because they are fairly slow and can be outrun even without snaring them. You must be SOW-ed because they will occasionally resist a snare. Once they are snared, though, I&#8217;ve never had the snare wear off, even during a protracted fight. I&#8217;ve even been able to run ahead, sit down to med, get hit, jump up, run ahead, sit down to med, jump up and cast the final blast before a snare wears off.<BR>
<BR>
The other nice thing about these MOB&#8217;s is that they give reasonably good experience and good loot including; split paw hides, masks, gloves, a couple plat or fine steel weapons (which easily fetch 3-6 PP) at a merchant. As well they drop two different types of tanned skins (rolled -up style and flat style) both of which are used in simple quests originating in Queynos. In fact, while fighting here in just level 30, I&#8217;ve collected enough of the first skins to complete the Gem Inlaid Gauntlet quest twice (these fetch about 100-200PP at auction). There are two other strange drops these Gnolls make &#8211; the preserved splitpaw which is a summon light globe artifact with five charges and the preserved splitpaw eye which acts like a visions enhancer. To use either, you simply equip it or place it in a primary slot and right click on it. I found the eyes to be useful here and at the FM Giant Fort when I wanted to see if a MOB was carrying a weapon without getting any closer.<BR>
<BR>
If solo-ing here (or in illomen) the first thing to do when logging in, or arriving in the zone is shout out a request for Breeze or Clarity. I gladly pay 5-10PP for these since they can speed up medding time and allow so much extra solo-ing to be conducted. Unfortunately Enchanters are hard to come by, especially in SK. <BR>
<BR>
As already stated, the Centaur Village is the next ideal hunting zone in this area and then the dungeon of Splitpaw itself. Since this is inside, traditional Druid tactics won&#8217;t apply and I&#8217;ve died several times in there. It really requires a group in order to be effective, but there is an experience bonus applied inside this zone.<BR>
<BR>
Another interesting area near SK is the Aviak village, which I&#8217;ve only slightly explored and the entrance to Lake Rathe to the South. When the Spires are crowded I run down here and into Lake Rathe. Right at the zone edge is a lower level Gnoll camp (at night, these spawns are replaced by undead). Although they don&#8217;t give any experience to my level 30 druid, I&#8217;m sure they are good for a low-mid 20&#8217;s player. Harmony is important here and they Gnolls should be pulled back toward SK so a hasty escape could be made, if necessary. Most importantly, they regularly drop a Runed Totem Staff, which is a nice magical 2HB weapon that sells for 15-20PP at auction.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Fazool Thunderwood<BR>
31th Season Druid (so far)<BR>
XEV Server<BR>
